     "text": [
      "cumulative explained variance: [0.164 0.301 0.428 0.554 0.679 0.8   0.913 1.   ]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "\n",
    "num_real = [\"credit_score\", \"age\", \"tenure\", \"balance\", \"products_number\",\n",
    "            \"credit_card\", \"active_member\", \"estimated_salary\"]\n",
    "Xp = StandardScaler().fit_transform(base[num_real])\n",
    "pca = PCA().fit(Xp)\n",
    "evr = pca.explained_variance_ratio_\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(13, 4.2))\n",
    "axes[0].bar(range(1, 9), evr, color=\"#4C72B0\", label=\"per component\")\n",
    "axes[0].plot(range(1, 9), np.cumsum(evr), \"o-\", color=\"#C44E52\", label=\"cumulative\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"PCA — explained variance\"); axes[0].set_xlabel(\"component\"); axes[0].legend()\n",
    "loads = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_[:4].T, index=num_real, columns=[\"PC1\", \"PC2\", \"PC3\", \"PC4\"])\n",
    "sns.heatmap(loads, annot=True, fmt=\".2f\", cmap=\"RdBu_r\", center=0, ax=axes[1])\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Loadings — first 4 components\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.savefig(f\"{FIG}/pca_real_v3.png\", dpi=120); plt.show()\n",
    "print(\"cumulative explained variance:\", np.round(np.cumsum(evr), 3))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-029",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Observations**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Variance is spread out: PC1 explains only 16.4% and 7 components are needed for 90% → **no dominant low-dimensional structure**; the real features are largely independent. PCA is kept as a diagnostic, not as a transform for modeling.\n",
    "- Interpretable axes: **PC1 = `balance` ↔ `products_number` opposition** (-0.70/+0.70); **PC2 = `age` + `active_member`** (0.59/0.69) — precisely the churn-relevant pair; PC4 ≈ `credit_score` alone.\n",
    "- Feature choice for Model B (§5.4): **`age`, `balance`, `products_number`, `active_member`, `credit_score`** — the 5 real demographic/financial features covering the leading axes; `tenure`/`credit_card`/`estimated_salary` are excluded (≈ zero churn signal in §4.2.3 and no distinct axis).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-030",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Factor Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**Question.** Do a small number of latent factors explain the shared variance (as opposed to PCA's total-variance view)?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "cell-031",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 550x400 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.decomposition import FactorAnalysis\n",
    "\n",
    "fa = FactorAnalysis(n_components=3, random_state=SEED).fit(Xp)\n",
    "fa_loads = pd.DataFrame(fa.components_.T, index=num_real, columns=[\"F1\", \"F2\", \"F3\"])\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5.5, 4))\n",
    "sns.heatmap(fa_loads, annot=True, fmt=\".2f\", cmap=\"RdBu_r\", center=0, ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Factor Analysis — loadings (3 factors)\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.savefig(f\"{FIG}/factor_analysis_v3.png\", dpi=120); plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-032",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Observations**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Only two weak common factors emerge: **F1 = `balance` ↔ `products_number`** (±0.56) and **F2 = `age` + `active_member`** (0.21/0.41); F3 ≈ nothing. Consistent with PCA: shared variance is limited to those two pairs.\n",
    "- Implication: dimensionality reduction would discard little redundancy but blur interpretability → keep original features for modeling; use the two factor axes only to justify the Model B feature set.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-033",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Cluster Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**Question.** Is there a natural number of clusters on the 5 selected real features, and is K=4 (the business-desired granularity for Q2) defensible?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "cell-034",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1100x380 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      " k   inertia  silhouette\n",
      " 2 39859.302       0.215\n",
      " 3 33813.848       0.218\n",
      " 4 29765.766       0.242\n",
      " 5 26228.566       0.250\n",
      " 6 23695.718       0.272\n",
      " 7 21786.690       0.285\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n",
    "\n",
    "seg_feats = [\"age\", \"balance\", \"products_number\", \"active_member\", \"credit_score\"]\n",
    "Xk_eda = StandardScaler().fit_transform(base[seg_feats])\n",
    "rows_k = []\n",
    "for k in range(2, 8):\n",
    "    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init=5, random_state=SEED).fit(Xk_eda)\n",
    "    rows_k.append((k, km.inertia_, silhouette_score(Xk_eda, km.labels_, sample_size=3000, random_state=SEED)))\n",
    "ktab = pd.DataFrame(rows_k, columns=[\"k\", \"inertia\", \"silhouette\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 3.8))\n",
    "axes[0].plot(ktab[\"k\"], ktab[\"inertia\"], \"o-\"); axes[0].set_title(\"Elbow — inertia vs k\"); axes[0].set_xlabel(\"k\")\n",
    "axes[1].plot(ktab[\"k\"], ktab[\"silhouette\"], \"o-\", color=\"#DD8452\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Silhouette vs k\"); axes[1].set_xlabel(\"k\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.savefig(f\"{FIG}/cluster_k_selection_v3.png\", dpi=120); plt.show()\n",
    "print(ktab.round(3).to_string(index=False))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-035",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Observations**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The elbow flattens gradually and silhouette rises monotonically (0.22 at k=2 → 0.24 at k=4 → 0.29 at k=7) with no peak → **no strong natural K**; the data's cluster structure is weak.\n",
    "- K=4 (silhouette ≈ 0.24) is adopted for Model B on business grounds — it matches the 4-segment granularity of Q2 and remains communicable; the weak structure is why rule-based segmentation (§4.3) stays primary and K-Means serves as a cross-check.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-036",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4.3 Segment Profiling\n",
    "\n",
    "**Goal:** assign every customer to one of 4 actionable groups (Q2): **Champion, Loyalist, Promising, At Risk** — real columns only.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Rules (priority-ordered, exhaustive & mutually exclusive) — derived from the §4.2.3 heatmap:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **At Risk** — `products_number ≥ 3` OR (`active_member = 0` AND `age ≥ 45`): the two highest-churn regions.\n",
    "2. **Champion** — active, `tenure ≥ 6`, `products = 2`: long-tenured, at the 2-product \"sweet spot\".\n",
    "3. **Promising** — `tenure ≤ 2`: new customers, early-lifecycle onboarding group.\n",
    "4. **Loyalist** — everyone else.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Methodological note:* rule-based descriptive segmentation validated against observed churn rates, not causal labeling; the K-Means cross-check happens in Model B (§5.4).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "cell-037",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
